Fully Qualified Keys in Calculated Insights

Add key qualifier fields to table joins and dimensions to ensure that your calculated insight computes data correctly. Using key qualifier fields is optional, but we recommend including them to ensure an accurate calculation of metrics and dimensions.

When you create a calculated insight using a SQL-based tool, the validation logic looks for key qualifier fields in all the table joins and in the Group By clause. If you don’t include key qualifier fields in your query, you get a warning message that lists the required key qualifier fields.

When you create a calculated insight using Insights Builder, Data Cloud adds the key qualifier fields to all table joins. The key qualifier field is also selected as a dimension in the Group By clause.

When you create a calculated insight query using a third-party tool, such as DBeaver, without key qualifier fields, the query runs successfully in the tool even if the results are incorrect. However, when you copy the SQL expression into Insight Builder to create a calculated insight, Data Cloud warns you that the query must include key qualifier fields in table joins and as a dimension.

EXAMPLE

This calculated insight query counts the number of encounters and the purpose of the encounters for a doctor by including key qualifier fields in the Join clause. In addition, the Group By clause includes the key qualifier field to group the results accurately. When you use this calculated insight in segmentation or Query API, the insight interprets the data correctly.

SELECT
COUNT(Encounters.Id) as count__c,
ssot__Individual__dlm.Id as doctor_id__c,
Encounters.Purpose as purpose__c,
ssot__Individual__dlm.KQ__Id as individual_KQ_id__c
FROM
ssot__Individual__dlm
JOIN Encounters ON Encounters.Doctor = ssot__Individual__dlm.Id
AND IFNULL(Encounters.KQ__Doctor, '') = IFNULL(Individual.KQ__Id, '')
GROUP BY
Doctor_id__c, purpose__c, individual_KQ_id__c
